1️⃣ What does wait() REALLY mean?
It means:
“I will give up this object’s lock and wait until someone tells me to continue.”

So wait() = release lock + pause

2️⃣ What is synchronized (b) doing?
synchronized (b) {
   // code
}
This means:

“Before entering, I must take the lock of object b.”
Only one thread can hold that lock at a time.



Very Simple Real-Life Example 🚪

Imagine:
b = a room
Lock = key of the room
synchronized(b) = you enter the room and take the key
wait() = you put the key on the table and sit inside waiting
❓ Can you put the key back if you never took it?
👉 NO

That’s why:
You must enter the room first (synchronized)
Then you can put the key down (wait())